# Frontend Motion & Interaction Governance

## Precedence

Authoritative for motion and interaction semantics.
For global conflict order, see `rules-index.mdc`.

## 1) Transition & Easing Rules

- Do not use `transition-all`.
- Always scope transitions to target properties:
  `transition-colors` / `transition-opacity` / `transition-shadow` / `transition-[...]`.
- **Tailwind CSS v4 (this repo):** transition the CSS property that Tailwind actually changes. Check DevTools → Computed when unsure.
  - `translate-x-*` / `translate-y-*` change CSS **`translate`**. Use `transition-[opacity,translate]` or `transition-[translate,...]`, not `transition-transform`.
  - `scale-*` changes CSS **`scale`**. Use `transition-[scale,...]` when scale is the moving part.
  - `rotate-*` changes CSS **`rotate`**. Use `transition-[rotate,...]` when rotation is the moving part.
  - Use `transition-transform` / `transition-[transform,...]` only when the actual `transform` shorthand changes.
- Recommended mappings:
  - Dropdown / popover slide: `transition-[opacity,translate]`
  - Card lift with `translate-*`: `transition-[translate,box-shadow]`
  - Card lift with `scale-*`: `transition-[scale,box-shadow]`
  - Button state: `transition-[background-color,color,box-shadow]`
  - Collapsible panels: `transition-[grid-template-rows,opacity]`
  - Progress bars: prefer `origin-left scale-x-*` with `transition-[scale]` (Tailwind v4); keep `transition-transform` only when the element animates the real CSS `transform` shorthand (e.g. inline `style={{ transform: ... }}`). Use `transition-[width]` only for intentional layout-width animation and document why.

### Easing

- Prefer exponential ease-out (`ease-out`, or custom `cubic-bezier` quart/quint) for natural deceleration on enters and state changes.
- Avoid bounce and elastic easing — they feel dated; real objects decelerate smoothly.
- For height/collapse animations, use `grid-template-rows` transitions (e.g. `0fr` → `1fr`) instead of animating `height` directly.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
className="transition-all hover:scale-105 hover:shadow-lg"

// ✅ GOOD — Tailwind v4 + `translate-*`: list `translate` in `transition-[...]` (see DevTools → Computed).
className="transition-[opacity,translate] opacity-0 translate-y-1 data-[state=open]:opacity-100 data-[state=open]:translate-y-0"
```

## 2) Interaction Semantics

- Only interactive elements may use `cursor-pointer`, hover interactions, or click feedback.
- Decorative elements must remove interaction affordances; add `aria-hidden` and/or `pointer-events-none` when appropriate.
- Avoid any UI that looks clickable but is not actually interactive.
- Use progressive disclosure — start simple, reveal complexity through interaction (basic options visible, advanced behind expandable sections; hover states that reveal secondary actions).
- Every interactive surface should feel responsive — provide immediate visual feedback on press/click.

## 3) Accessibility Baseline

- Interactive controls must provide at least a `44x44` touch target on mobile.
- Do not rely on `group-hover` alone for critical actions; touch and keyboard users must also access them.
- New motion must support `prefers-reduced-motion`.
- **Skip to main**: `src/app/[locale]/layout.tsx` renders `SkipToMainLink` first; every primary content shell must expose exactly one `main` with `id="main-content"` and `tabIndex={-1}`. Full-page fallbacks (`404`, `error`, `ProfileDataLoadError`) that render without a nested layout must wrap content in that same `main`.

## 4) Color & Hero Gradient Rules

- Do not hardcode long-lived business UI colors (for example `#hex`, `purple-*`, `green-*` semantic leakage).
- Prefer semantic design tokens first (`primary`, `accent`, `success`, `chart-*`).
- Feature hero gradients must use preset/config-driven definitions, not scattered inline combinations.

### Headline emphasis (accessibility)

- **Do not** use `background-clip: text` / `bg-clip-text text-transparent` with gradients for primary headline copy (`h1`–`h2` text users read). Per-pixel contrast is uneven and hard to verify for WCAG 1.4.3.
- **Do** use solid semantic text colors for emphasized spans: **`text-primary`** (or `text-foreground` for the non-emphasized part). `FEATURE_HERO_GRADIENTS.highlight` must be a text utility such as `text-primary`, not a `bg-linear-to-*` + clip pair.
- **May** keep gradients on **non-text** surfaces: section backgrounds (`section`), glow orbs, borders, decorative meshes — still token-driven.
- **Exception**: purely decorative non-headline effects (e.g. loading shimmer) may use clip techniques; they must not carry sole semantic meaning for titles.

## 5) Media & Performance Rules

- Prefer `next/image` for presentational images and provide correct `sizes`.
- Animate compositor-friendly properties only (`opacity`, plus `translate` / `scale` / `rotate` / `transform` depending on what Tailwind emits — see §1 Tailwind v4 note). Do not animate layout properties (`width`, `height`, `padding`, `margin`) unless the layout change is intentional and localized.
- For orchestrated page loads, use staggered reveals (`animation-delay`) — one well-sequenced entrance creates more impact than scattered micro-interactions.

## 6) PR Self-check

- [ ] `transition-all` count is 0 within changed scope
- [ ] No pseudo-clickable elements
- [ ] Touch target and non-hover accessibility requirements are met
- [ ] Color and gradient usage follow token/preset rules
- [ ] Animations use `opacity` plus the same motion properties Tailwind actually sets (`translate` / `scale` / `rotate` / `transform`) — no layout property animations unless explicitly justified
- [ ] No bounce/elastic easing; easing feels smooth and natural
- [ ] Lint passes
